PEDV antigens were also frequently detected in the intestinal crypt cells or antigen presenting cells, such as macrophages, in the lamina propria or Peyer's patches (
 Debouck et al., 1981; 
 Jung et al., 2014; 
 Lin et al., 2015a; 
 Madson et al., 2016; 
 Stevenson et al., 2013; 
 Sueyoshi et al., 1995). PEDV remains infectious in dendritic cells for <24 h 
 in vitro (
 Gao et al., 2015), but dendritic cells may not be a site of PEDV replication (
 Wang et al., 2017). Instead, PEDV appeared to employ dendritic cells to cross the epithelial barrier of the nasal cavity (
 Li et al., 2018). Lung tissues of oronasally infected pigs were negative for PEDV antigen (
 Debouck et al., 1981; 
 Jung et al., 2014; 
 Stevenson et al., 2013; 
 Sueyoshi et al., 1995). However, the upper respiratory tract may be the site of PEDV infection, because the epithelium lining the nasal cavity was positive for PEDV antigens (
 Li et al., 2018). Although acute viremia was frequently noted in infected pigs during the acute or incubation stage of infection (
 Jung et al., 2018, 
 2014; 
 Madson et al., 2016), PEDV antigens were not detected in other major organs, such as liver and kidneys (
 Debouck et al., 1981; 
 Jung et al., 2014; 
 Stevenson et al., 2013; 
 Sueyoshi et al., 1995). The reproductive organs of experimentally infected boars, such as Cowpersâ€™s glands, were also negative for PEDV RNA, but their semen was transiently positive for PEDV RNA (
 Gallien et al., 2018b, 
 2019). Nevertheless, whether the PEDV RNA-positive semen contained infectious viral particles is unclear.
